  <!-- FAQ Section -->
  <section class="faq-section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header">
        <span class="section-tag">FAQs</span>
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <p>Common questions about the best credit cards in India for 2026</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question">
            Which is the best credit card in India in 2026?
            <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">
              The best credit card depends on your spending habits and lifestyle. For premium travellers, HDFC Infinia and Diners Club Black are top choices with unlimited lounge access and high reward rates. For everyday spending, ICICI Amazon Pay and Axis ACE offer excellent value as lifetime free cards with 2-5% returns. For cashback lovers, SBI Cashback and HDFC Millennia deliver strong returns on online and offline spends. We recommend comparing cards based on your primary spending category.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question">
            How do we rank the best credit cards?
            <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">
              Our expert team evaluates credit cards across six key parameters: (1) Annual fee vs. value delivered, (2) Reward earn rate and redemption flexibility, (3) Welcome benefits and milestone bonuses, (4) Additional perks like lounge access, insurance, and concierge, (5) Customer reviews and satisfaction scores, (6) Ease of application and approval rates. Cards are scored on a 100-point scale and ranked within their respective categories before being compiled into our overall best list.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question">
            Can I get a top-rated credit card with a 700 CIBIL score?
            <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">
              Yes, a CIBIL score of 700 qualifies you for many excellent credit cards, including ICICI Amazon Pay (lifetime free, 5% for Prime members), HDFC Millennia (5% cashback online), and Axis Flipkart (5% on Flipkart). For super-premium cards like HDFC Infinia or Diners Black, a score of 750+ is typically required along with a higher income threshold. You can improve your chances by applying through your existing bank where you have a salary or savings account.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question">
            Is it better to get a free card or a paid premium card?
            <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">
              It depends on your annual spending. If you spend less than ₹3-4 lakh per year, a lifetime free card like ICICI Amazon Pay or Axis ACE typically delivers the best value since you pay no fees and still earn 2-5% returns. However, if you spend ₹6-10 lakh or more annually, premium paid cards like HDFC Regalia or SBI Elite can deliver far more value through lounge access, travel benefits, and accelerated rewards that far exceed the annual fee. Calculate your expected rewards versus the fee before deciding.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question">
            How many credit cards should I have?
            <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">
              Financial experts recommend holding 2-3 credit cards for optimal benefits. One card can be your primary spending card with the best overall rewards, a second card can target a specific high-spend category (like travel or fuel), and a third can serve as a backup or for its unique perks. Having multiple cards also helps improve your credit utilisation ratio, which positively impacts your CIBIL score. However, avoid applying for too many cards in a short period, as each application creates a hard inquiry on your credit report.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

